description: From Middle English temen (“to bear, to support”), from Old English tēman (“to give birth”).

verbs.description: teem (third-person singular simple present teems, present participle teeming, simple past and past participle teemed)

entries.meaning: To be prolific; to abound; to be rife.
(obsolete) To bring forth young, as an animal; to produce fruit, as a plant; to bear; to be pregnant; to conceive; to multiply.

description: From Middle English temen (“to drain”), from Old Norse tœma, from Proto-Germanic *tōmijaną (“to empty, make empty”). Related to English toom (“empty, vacant”). More at toom.

verbs.description: teem (third-person singular simple present teems, present participle teeming, simple past and past participle teemed)

examples: [The banksman] also puts the full tubs to the weighing machine, and thence to the skreens, upon which he teems the coals. It is also his duty to keep an account of the quantity of coals and stones drawn each day.

entries.meaning: To pour, as steel, from a melting pot; to fill, as a mould, with molten metal.

description: From Middle English temen (“to be suitable, befit”), from Old English *teman, from Proto-Germanic *temaną (“to fit”). Cognate with Low German temen, tamen (“to befit”), Dutch betamen (“to befit”), German ziemen. See also tame (adjective) and compare beteem.

verbs.description: teem (third-person singular simple present teems, present participle teeming, simple past and past participle teemed)

examples: Ah, said he, thou hast confessed and bewrayed all, I could teem it to rend thee in pieces
